
Nancy Cooke de Herrera (born Nancy Veitch, 1922&lt;U+2013&gt;2013)1 was an American socialite, fashion expert, and author of three books, including All You Need Is Love: An Eyewitness Account of When Spirituality Spread from the East to the West.23 She was referred to as one of the pioneers of the spiritual movement in the West.
Early life and education
De Herrera grew up in Piedmont, California and studied bacteriology at Stanford University for three years in the 1940s (Class of '43).45
Adult life
De Herrera traveled to Molokai in Hawaii via a military convoy and married Richard Cooke, the son of a well-known missionary family in 1941.67 As the wife of a prominent family member, she performed hostess duties for Admiral Nimitz, Admiral Halsey, and Admiral Towers during World War II. She gave birth to three sons and divorced her husband after nine years of marriage.
While in Paris in 1951, she met a member of the American team that raced at Le Mans, named Luis de Herrera, whom she married a year later. The couple moved to Herrera's home country of Argentina and had a daughter in 1954.8 Nine months later her husband, Luis, died of leukemia believed to be related to atomic radiation exposure the couple had incurred while driving near Zion National Park just after an atomic bomb test in 1953.9101112
In 1957, de Herrera won a nationwide contest sponsored by a group of American (USA) magazines. Her prize was a world tour to promote American fashion. Afterwards, the United States Information Service (USIS) enabled her to visit governments around the world and advise them on fashion.13 For twelve years she was a leading figure in the fashion industry and was referred to as the &quot;U.S. Ambassadress of Fashion&quot; while traveling to 15 countries to present American couture.141516 She also presented lectures entitled: &quot;A Travelogue through Fashion&quot; and &quot;Around the World with Nancy Cooke&quot;.17
De Herrera worked as a publicist for Maharishi Mahesh Yogi in the 1960s and traveled with him on a trip to South America.1819 She was the liaison for the Maharishi and The Beatles during their widely publicized visit to Rishikesh in India.20 During her dozens of trips to India and Tibet she is reported to have had meetings with the Dalai Lama, the sixteenth Gyalwa Karmapa, Sir Edmund Hillary, the Shah of Iran, King Hussein of Jordan, and Satya Sai Baba.21 In 1993, she published the autobiographical memoir, Beyond Gurus: A Woman Of Many Worlds, and in 2003, published a follow-up book called, All You Need Is Love: An Eyewitness Account of When Spirituality Spread from the East to the West.22
Over the years she was reported to have given meditation lessons to many celebrities, including Madonna, Greta Garbo, Rosie O'Donnell, Lenny Kravitz, Santigold,23 and Sheryl Crow.2425 She was called one of the pioneers of the spiritual movement in the West.26 In 2008, she published the novel, Never Tango with a Stranger: Love in Peron's Argentina.27 According to de Herrera, with the help of friends, she built two hospitals for abused children in Los Angeles.28
De Herrera died on February 28, 2013 at the age of 90.29 She was reportedly working on a third autobiography, concerning her role as the U.S. Ambassadress of Fashion in the 1950s when she died.30
Books

Cooke de Herrera, Nancy (1993) Beyond gurus : a woman of many worlds, Blue Dolphin Pub.31
